00:06:14,640 --> 00:06:16,260
Well, the next step, surely,

160
00:06:16,260 --> 00:06:18,000
we just need to get ourselves connected.

161
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:19,623
We just plug in, don't we?

162
00:06:20,460 --> 00:06:21,750
Well, the photo that I'm showing you here,

163
00:06:21,750 --> 00:06:23,820
this is an example of a meet-me room.

164
00:06:23,820 --> 00:06:26,070
So this is Equinix TY2.

165
00:06:26,070 --> 00:06:28,230
And as you can see, it's
full of a lot of fiber,

166
00:06:28,230 --> 00:06:29,790
a lot of ports.

167
00:06:29,790 --> 00:06:33,570
This is actually a very,
very tidy, neat meet-me room.

168
00:06:33,570 --> 00:06:36,480
And this is where your port from AWS

169
00:06:36,480 --> 00:06:38,910
is presented for you to consume.

170
00:06:38,910 --> 00:06:40,560
So when you order that connection,

171
00:06:40,560 --> 00:06:43,620
we then issue something called an LOA CFA.

172
00:06:43,620 --> 00:06:45,720
So an LOA is a letter of authorization.

173
00:06:45,720 --> 00:06:49,620
It is your permission to
plug into a particular port.

174
00:06:49,620 --> 00:06:52,290
And CFA is the Connecting
Facility Assignment.

175
00:06:52,290 --> 00:06:54,870
It's basically where is that port.

176
00:06:54,870 --> 00:06:56,910
So this document contains
everything you need

177
00:06:56,910 --> 00:06:58,140
to be able to plug into that

178
00:06:58,140 --> 00:06:59,740
Direct Connect port on our side.

179
00:07:00,660 --> 00:07:02,610
It's gonna contain other information,

180
00:07:02,610 --> 00:07:04,320
such as the connector type.

181
00:07:04,320 --> 00:07:07,590
So LC connector is
typically what we would see.

182
00:07:07,590 --> 00:07:09,150
It's a single-mode connection.

183
00:07:09,150 --> 00:07:10,620
The different standards that are required

184
00:07:10,620 --> 00:07:13,260
for the different
bandwidths for our ports.

185
00:07:13,260 --> 00:07:15,270
So you've got all that information.

186
00:07:15,270 --> 00:07:19,020
So surely now, you just plug in, yeah?

187
00:07:19,020 --> 00:07:20,790
No, that's not quite how it goes.

188
00:07:20,790 --> 00:07:24,360
Because in reality, you
personally, as a customer,

189
00:07:24,360 --> 00:07:26,910
probably do not have access
to that meet-me room.

190
00:07:26,910 --> 00:07:28,470
So in reality, you're gonna have to work

191
00:07:28,470 --> 00:07:30,040
with the co-location provider now

192
00:07:30,040 --> 00:07:32,360
to arrange for something
called a cross-connect

193
00:07:32,360 --> 00:07:35,190
between that port that we've allocated

194
00:07:35,190 --> 00:07:36,483
and your infrastructure.

195
00:07:37,500 --> 00:07:40,110
So when we think about getting connected,

196
00:07:40,110 --> 00:07:43,410
unfortunately, there have to
be multiple people involved

197
00:07:43,410 --> 00:07:45,090
in making this connection.

198
00:07:45,090 --> 00:07:48,210
It's not something that you
can own totally yourself.

199
00:07:48,210 --> 00:07:51,060
There's always gonna be at
least three parties involved.

200
00:07:51,060 --> 00:07:52,950
There's obviously AWS on one side,

201
00:07:52,950 --> 00:07:54,690
providing the Direct Connect port.

202
00:07:54,690 --> 00:07:57,240
There's your side of
things, your infrastructure.

203
00:07:57,240 --> 00:07:59,360
And in the middle, we've got
this co-location provider

204
00:07:59,360 --> 00:08:01,710
that needs to make the cross-connect.

205
00:08:01,710 --> 00:08:03,750
The reality also is,
though, if you're connecting

206
00:08:03,750 --> 00:08:05,370
to a facility that is outside

207
00:08:05,370 --> 00:08:07,800
of that particular co-location facility,

208
00:08:07,800 --> 00:08:09,360
then you're probably gonna have to work

209
00:08:09,360 --> 00:08:11,970
with some sort of telco partner, carrier,

210
00:08:11,970 --> 00:08:14,850
maybe even a separate last-mile provider.

211
00:08:14,850 --> 00:08:16,980
And unfortunately, all
of the people involved

212
00:08:16,980 --> 00:08:19,260
probably have their own processes,

213
00:08:19,260 --> 00:08:21,270
their own ways of doing testing.

214
00:08:21,270 --> 00:08:22,800
And I'll come onto this later on,

215
00:08:22,800 --> 00:08:25,290
perhaps their own polarity on their ports

216
00:08:25,290 --> 00:08:27,300
causes some interesting challenges.

217
00:08:27,300 --> 00:08:29,820
So I've been doing this
for quite a few years.

218
00:08:29,820 --> 00:08:31,950
I've worked on a bunch
of customer projects

219
00:08:31,950 --> 00:08:34,230
and internal projects
involving Direct Connect,

220
00:08:34,230 --> 00:08:36,630
and I thought I'd just
share a couple of tips

221
00:08:36,630 --> 00:08:38,700
from my experiences.

222
00:08:38,700 --> 00:08:40,530
And the first one is, I would say,

223
00:08:40,530 --> 00:08:43,290
