achieve with Direct Connect.

225
00:08:46,080 --> 00:08:49,080
Put AWS on one side, put your
infrastructure on the other,

226
00:08:49,080 --> 00:08:52,410
and then work out all of the
pieces involved in the middle.

227
00:08:52,410 --> 00:08:54,780
Doesn't have to be fancy,
just a very simple diagram

228
00:08:54,780 --> 00:08:56,130
that shows all the locations,

229
00:08:56,130 --> 00:08:58,140
perhaps all the devices
that you're aware of

230
00:08:58,140 --> 00:09:00,570
that these connections
are gonna go through.

231
00:09:00,570 --> 00:09:03,750
On that diagram, identify
who owns each component,

232
00:09:03,750 --> 00:09:05,910
because they will all
have different owners.

233
00:09:05,910 --> 00:09:08,820
And then every port ID,
every circuit number,

234
00:09:08,820 --> 00:09:10,410
everything you see written in an email

235
00:09:10,410 --> 00:09:12,360
or said to you over the phone,

236
00:09:12,360 --> 00:09:13,800
just add it onto that diagram.

237
00:09:13,800 --> 00:09:15,240
And this will become your reference

238
00:09:15,240 --> 00:09:18,420
for everything to do with that
particular Direct Connect.

239
00:09:18,420 --> 00:09:20,280
I also find it quite useful
just to note on there

240
00:09:20,280 --> 00:09:21,600
things like support details,

241
00:09:21,600 --> 00:09:23,580
contact details for the people involved,

242
00:09:23,580 --> 00:09:24,600
because this, as I say,

243
00:09:24,600 --> 00:09:27,560
just becomes your
reference going forwards.

244
00:09:27,560 --> 00:09:30,600
So how do we put all the
pieces together here?

245
00:09:30,600 --> 00:09:32,970
So what I wanted to start
with was the example

246
00:09:32,970 --> 00:09:35,550
where you've got infrastructure
in your own facility,

247
00:09:35,550 --> 00:09:37,080
perhaps your own data center.

248
00:09:37,080 --> 00:09:38,970
It's not within the
Direct Connect location,

249
00:09:38,970 --> 00:09:42,600
so in my example earlier,
the Equinix TY2 facility.

250
00:09:42,600 --> 00:09:44,400
And we want to establish this connection

251
00:09:44,400 --> 00:09:46,890
from an AWS Direct Connect port

252
00:09:46,890 --> 00:09:49,590
all the way through to your equipment.

253
00:09:49,590 --> 00:09:51,990
Now it'd be really nice if you
could just fire off an email

254
00:09:51,990 --> 00:09:55,087
that says, "Hey, partner, could
you just make this happen?

255
00:09:55,087 --> 00:09:58,087
"Here's the LOA from
AWS, here's my equipment.

256
00:09:58,087 --> 00:10:01,260
"Could you just connect the two together?"

257
00:10:01,260 --> 00:10:03,120
I'm not gonna lie, there are some cases

258
00:10:03,120 --> 00:10:04,200
where you can do that.

259
00:10:04,200 --> 00:10:06,450
There are some excellent partners

260
00:10:06,450 --> 00:10:09,930
who have all of the ability
to deliver this end-to-end.

261
00:10:09,930 --> 00:10:11,580
But unfortunately, the reality is

262
00:10:11,580 --> 00:10:14,880
there are usually many
more components involved.

263
00:10:14,880 --> 00:10:16,650
But let's stick with
the example for a moment

264
00:10:16,650 --> 00:10:19,380
where we've asked a partner to deliver it,

265
00:10:19,380 --> 00:10:21,360
and in which case, they simply build

266
00:10:21,360 --> 00:10:22,260
all these connections.

267
00:10:22,260 --> 00:10:24,390
So perhaps they arrange the last mile

268
00:10:24,390 --> 00:10:27,300
from your data center
to a point of presence

269
00:10:27,300 --> 00:10:30,030
in your city for their infrastructure.

270
00:10:30,030 --> 00:10:32,340
Maybe then they configure
across the backbone

271
00:10:32,340 --> 00:10:35,670
that they have over their
optical network into a location,

272
00:10:35,670 --> 00:10:37,500
and they arrange it all, fantastic.

273
00:10:37,500 --> 00:10:41,283
They plug it in, ports come
up on your router, happy days.

274
00:10:42,870 --> 00:10:45,150
As I say, the reality is
a little bit different.

275
00:10:45,150 --> 00:10:47,580
Now, the infrastructure I mentioned there

276
00:10:47,580 --> 00:10:49,860
is in place typically, so there will be

277
00:10:49,860 --> 00:10:51,540
points of presence in your city.

278
00:10:51,540 --> 00:10:52,800
There will be infrastructure in

279
00:10:52,800 --> 00:10:54,210
these co-location facilities

280
00:10:54,210 --> 00:10:56,910
from the various telcos and carriers.

281
00:10:56,910 --> 00:10:59,790
Also, there is the meet-me
room infrastructure

282
00:10:59,790 --> 00:11:01,920
that I mentioned a moment ago.

283
00:11:01,920 --> 00:11:04,470
AWS's equipment is already pre-cabled

284
00:11:04,470 --> 00:11:07,230
from our devices directly
into that meet-me room,

285
00:11:07,230 --> 00:11:09,450
into what you saw in the photo earlier on.

286
00:11:09,450 --> 00:11:11,790
And the chances are
that the large carriers

287
00:11:11,790 --> 00:11:13,120
and telcos in these facilities

288
00:11:13,120 --> 00:11:16,530
are also pre-cabled to the meet-me room.

289
00:11:16,530 --> 00:11:18,690
So what that means is we
still have a few gaps,

290
00:11:18,690 --> 00:11:21,570
but it's not quite as bad
as I showed a moment ago.

291
00:11:21,570 --> 00:11:24,030
But to make all these connections happen,

292
00:11:24,030 --> 00:11:25,530
you can imagine there's gonna be

293
00:11:25,530 --> 00:11:27,480
a lot of communication going on.

294
00:11:27,480 --> 00:11:30,240
There's gonna be the
request from the owner

295
00:11:30,240 --> 00:11:32,610
of the telecoms equipment to request

296
00:11:32,610 --> 00:11:34,440
the cross-connect in the first place.

297
00:11:34,440 --> 00:11:36,150
There's gonna be provisioning of ports

298
00:11:36,150 --> 00:11:38,340
and circuits across the infrastructure.

299
00:11:38,340 --> 00:11:39,780
There's probably gonna be some ordering

300
00:11:39,780 --> 00:11:41,940
of running fiber across a town.

301
00:11:41,940 --> 00:11:44,520
There might even be
involvement of logistics

302
00:11:44,520 --> 00:11:46,470
to dig up the road to run fiber.

303
00:11:46,470 --> 00:11:48,940
All sorts of things could be involved.

304
00:11:48,940 --> 00:11:50,250
But when it comes down to it,

305
00:11:50,250 --> 00:11:52,320
if you break down that simple diagram

306
00:11:52,320 --> 00:11:54,510
and do it in stages, the first piece

307
00:11:54,510 --> 00:11:56,550
is that cross-connect in the meet-me room.

308
00:11:56,550 --> 00:11:59,060
So in this case, the telco has had to ask

309
00:11:59,060 --> 00:12:02,610
Equinix in our example to
make that cross-connect.

310
00:12:02,610 --> 00:12:05,160
The telco has then had to
make physical connections

311
00:12:05,160 --> 00:12:07,830
between patch panels in their
rack and their equipment,

312
00:12:07,830 --> 00:12:10,080
configure circuits over their network,

313
00:12:10,080 --> 00:12:12,210
deliver it to your local city,

314
00:12:12,210 --> 00:12:14,460
perhaps dig up some streets,

315
00:12:14,460 --> 00:12:16,110
and then deliver it into your location

316
00:12:16,110 --> 00:12:18,560
presented on a port ready
to go into your router.

317
00:12:19,720 --> 00:12:22,020
And at that point, we
might have a connection.

318
00:12:23,460 --> 00:12:27,120
The other variation on
this is if you are located

319
00:12:27,120 --> 00:12:29,790
inside that co-location facility already.

320
00:12:29,790 --> 00:12:31,950
Now if you're in there, things
are clearly a lot simpler.

321
00:12:31,950 --> 00:12:34,740
You don't have any of that
external telecoms work to do.

322
00:12:34,740 --> 00:12:37,350
So you'll have your rack, your equipment.

323
00:12:37,350 --> 00:12:40,470
Chances are you're also
pre-cabled to the meet-me room.

324
00:12:40,470 --> 00:12:42,030
If you're not familiar
with that experience,

325
00:12:42,030 --> 00:12:43,530
typically the first time you order

326
00:12:43,530 --> 00:12:46,020
any sort of cross-connect
in many of these facilities,

327
00:12:46,020 --> 00:12:47,700
they will install a whole set of fiber

328
00:12:47,700 --> 00:12:49,890
between your rack and the meet-me room.

329
00:12:49,890 --> 00:12:52,770
And what that means is you
can now interact directly

330
00:12:52,770 --> 00:12:54,420
with that location provider.

331
00:12:54,420 --> 00:12:56,640
So it really is as simple
as then sending the email

332
00:12:56,640 --> 00:12:59,040
that says, "Please can you
make this cross-connect?"

333
00:12:59,040 --> 00:13:00,300
And of course, it might not be an email.

334
00:13:00,300 --> 00:13:01,920
Different providers use portals.

335
00:13:01,920 --> 00:13:03,630
You might upload the details,

336
00:13:03,630 --> 00:13:06,030
provide the document we
give you as evidence.

337
00:13:06,030 --> 00:13:08,880
But effectively, you just
order that cross-connect

338
00:13:08,880 --> 00:13:09,713
and it's done.

339
00:13:10,590 --> 00:13:12,360
I've said cross-connect a couple of times.

340
00:13:12,360 --> 00:13:14,620
A cross-connect really
is just a piece of fiber

341
00:13:14,620 --> 00:13:16,620
being plugged into one port on one side

342
00:13:16,620 --> 00:13:18,300
and another port on the other.

343
00:13:18,300 --> 00:13:19,500
There's nothing more to it.

344
00:13:19,500 --> 00:13:21,840
I regularly get asked, "What
is this cross-connect thing?"

345
00:13:21,840 --> 00:13:23,130
And it's very simple.

346
00:13:23,130 --> 00:13:24,483
It's just a piece of fiber.

347
00:13:26,550 --> 00:13:29,160
So at that point, our connection comes up

348
00:13:29,160 --> 00:13:32,400
and hopefully the thing
you see in the AWS console

349
00:13:32,400 --> 00:13:34,500
is that your port goes from being down

350
00:13:34,500 --> 00:13:36,150
to now showing as available.

351
00:13:36,150 --> 00:13:38,490
The link comes up on your router.

352
00:13:38,490 --> 00:13:40,140
We're in a good place.

353
00:13:40,140 --> 00:13:41,370
But let's just go and verify

354
00:13:41,370 --> 00:13:43,500
that everything is as we expect.

355
00:13:43,500 --> 00:13:46,260
So we have CloudWatch
monitoring for Direct Connect.

356
00:13:46,260 --> 00:13:47,733
There's a whole bunch of the metrics

357
00:13:47,733 --> 00:13:49,290
that you would expect to see there,

358
00:13:49,290 --> 00:13:50,940
bandwidth usage, et cetera.

359
00:13:50,940 --> 00:13:52,290
But I wanted to just draw your attention

360
00:13:52,290 --> 00:13:53,760
to the connection state,

361
00:13:53,760 --> 00:13:55,650
which is a very simple
metric you can look at

362
00:13:55,650 --> 00:13:58,830
that indicates, is the
connection up or down?

363
00:13:58,830 --> 00:14:00,150
If it's one, it's up.

364
00:14:00,150 --> 00:14:02,100
Anything else, it's down.

365
00:14:02,100 --> 00:14:04,440
The other interesting ones to look at here

366
00:14:04,440 --> 00:14:07,170
are the light levels, particularly the RX,

367
00:14:07,170 --> 00:14:08,910
so the receive light level.

368
00:14:08,910 --> 00:14:10,080
And you can see on there,

369
00:14:10,080 --> 00:14:14,550
I've made a note of the ranges
that are considered good.

370
00:14:14,550 --> 00:14:18,330
Effectively, if you
get down to neg 12 DBM,

371
00:14:18,330 --> 00:14:20,820
you're okay, but you could be better.

372
00:14:20,820 --> 00:14:22,230
Start getting beyond that,

373
00:14:22,230 --> 00:14:24,390
this connection probably isn't coming up.

374
00:14:24,390 --> 00:14:25,363
And the reason I'm mentioning this

375
00:14:25,363 --> 00:14:27,600
is you can have a situation where

376
00:14:27,600 --> 00:14:29,400
everything is plugged in and connected,

377
00:14:29,400 --> 00:14:31,050
but you haven't got a link yet.

378
00:14:31,050 --> 00:14:32,760
And it's good to come and
have a look in the console

379
00:14:32,760 --> 00:14:34,740
and actually see what the light level is

380
00:14:34,740 --> 00:14:37,260
because it may well all be
connected absolutely fine,

381
00:14:37,260 --> 00:14:39,180
but you might have some
dirty fiber somewhere

382
00:14:39,180 --> 00:14:40,710
that wasn't cleaned when it was connected

383
00:14:40,710 --> 00:14:43,920
or something like that
that's attenuating the light

384
00:14:43,920 --> 00:14:46,680
that means we've not got
enough signal getting through.

385
00:14:46,680 --> 00:14:49,323
So always go take a look
at the CloudWatch metrics.

386
00:14:51,240 --> 00:14:53,010
Everything I've been talking about so far

387
00:14:53,010 --> 00:14:55,800
is what we refer to as
a dedicated connection.

388
00:14:55,800 --> 00:14:57,180
And it's exactly what it sounds like.

389
00:14:57,180 --> 00:14:59,820
This is a dedicated port
on a piece of AWS equipment

390
00:14:59,820 --> 00:15:01,260
that is assigned to you.

391
00:15:01,260 --> 00:15:04,260
You requested it and
we allocated it to you.

392
00:15:04,260 --> 00:15:06,180
You get full use of that port

393
00:15:06,180 --> 00:15:08,300
and the bandwidth available on it.

394
00:15:08,300 --> 00:15:10,920
It will support multiple
virtual interfaces,

395
00:15:10,920 --> 00:15:13,320
which we're gonna explain a
little bit more in a moment,

396
00:15:13,320 --> 00:15:16,260
but that's effectively
multiple VLANs and BGP sessions

397
00:15:16,260 --> 00:15:18,900
because you're in control of
everything about that port.

398
00:15:18,900 --> 00:15:20,840
Fundamentally, it is physical connectivity

399
00:15:20,840 --> 00:15:24,000
that you're responsible
for to get to the port

400
00:15:24,000 --> 00:15:25,400
that we've allocated to you.

401
00:15:26,250 --> 00:15:28,860
Hosted connections are
a little bit different.

402
00:15:28,860 --> 00:15:31,290
What happens here is
we allocate connections

403
00:15:31,290 --> 00:15:33,330
to one of our Direct Connect partners,

404
00:15:33,330 --> 00:15:35,160
and we actually call them
interconnects at that point.

405
00:15:35,160 --> 00:15:37,050
You may see that term around.

406
00:15:37,050 --> 00:15:39,540
And our partners have
already then taken care

407
00:15:39,540 --> 00:15:41,400
of all that physical connectivity

408
00:15:41,400 --> 00:15:44,130
between their infrastructure and ours.

409
00:15:44,130 --> 00:15:46,890
What they then do is allocate
smaller amounts of bandwidth

410
00:15:46,890 --> 00:15:49,650
on that connectivity to
you and provide it to you

411
00:15:49,650 --> 00:15:52,080
perhaps over an existing fabric or service

412
00:15:52,080 --> 00:15:54,483
they might have with you as a customer.

413
00:15:55,350 --> 00:15:58,800
In that case, our partners can
increase their connectivity

414
00:15:58,800 --> 00:16:01,110
with us by combining connections together.

415
00:16:01,110 --> 00:16:03,150
They can create lags just like you can,

416
00:16:03,150 --> 00:16:05,220
and we'll explain that in a moment.

417
00:16:05,220 --> 00:16:06,900
But they can increase that capacity,

418
00:16:06,900 --> 00:16:09,180
but we don't let partners
oversubscribe those ports.

419
00:16:09,180 --> 00:16:11,580
So as they allocate bandwidth to you,

420
00:16:11,580 --> 00:16:13,260
that bandwidth is passed on to you,

421
00:16:13,260 --> 00:16:15,240
and they have to expand their connectivity

422
00:16:15,240 --> 00:16:16,760
with us over time.

423
00:16:16,760 --> 00:16:18,620
The thing about hosted connection is

424
00:16:18,620 --> 00:16:20,820
you can only have one virtual interface

425
00:16:20,820 --> 00:16:22,470
per hosted connection.

426
00:16:22,470 --> 00:16:24,000
So it's quite common for our customers

427
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:25,860
to have multiple hosted connections

428
00:16:25,860 --> 00:16:27,930
if they need them for different workloads,

429
00:16:27,930 --> 00:16:30,450
perhaps some for virtual private gateways

430
00:16:30,450 --> 00:16:32,500
and some for transit gateways, et cetera.

431
00:16:33,480 --> 00:16:36,870
I mentioned their lags,
link aggregation groups.

432
00:16:36,870 --> 00:16:38,700
So what a link aggregation group is,

433
00:16:38,700 --> 00:16:41,660
is it allows you to combine
multiple physical connections

434
00:16:41,660 --> 00:16:45,210
into one single thing that is treated

435
00:16:45,210 --> 00:16:47,160
as a dedicated connection.

436
00:16:47,160 --> 00:16:50,550
So you might combine together
four 10 gig connections.

437
00:16:50,550 --> 00:16:53,220
So you have a resulting
40 gig of capacity there,

438
00:16:53,220 --> 00:16:54,930
but you treat it as a single connection

439
00:16:54,930 --> 00:16:56,880
when you're configuring
virtual interfaces,

440
00:16:56,880 --> 00:16:58,260
et cetera, on it.

441
00:16:58,260 --> 00:16:59,940
We'll then do flow hashing of the traffic

442
00:16:59,940 --> 00:17:01,500
across those connections,

443
00:17:01,500 --> 00:17:05,190
and you can configure on the
AWS side and your equipment,

444
00:17:05,190 --> 00:17:06,063
what is the appropriate point

445
00:17:06,063 --> 00:17:09,420
that you would rather shut
down that set of connections

446
00:17:09,420 --> 00:17:12,120
if you lose capacity
versus maintaining it.

447
00:17:12,120 --> 00:17:14,520
So you might have 40 gig of connectivity

448
00:17:14,520 --> 00:17:16,260
and you decide that you really need

449
00:17:16,260 --> 00:17:18,960
to always have 20 gig available.

450
00:17:18,960 --> 00:17:21,390
So if one of those other
connections is impacted,

451
00:17:21,390 --> 00:17:24,660
you're down to 30 gig,
that's fine, keep the lag up.

452
00:17:24,660 --> 00:17:27,030
But if we drop down to 20 gig or below,

453
00:17:27,030 --> 00:17:28,410
perhaps we then shut it down.

454
00:17:28,410 --> 00:17:30,240
And that's configured
as the minimum number

455
00:17:30,240 --> 00:17:31,743
of interfaces on a lag.

456
00:17:33,150 --> 00:17:36,090
So we're in a fairly
good place at this point.

457
00:17:36,090 --> 00:17:39,810
We've assumed everything's
working, but what if it doesn't?

458
00:17:39,810 --> 00:17:41,430
And what I thought I'd do is just talk you

459
00:17:41,430 --> 00:17:42,840
through a couple of situations

460
00:17:42,840 --> 00:17:44,280
that we hear about all the time,

461
00:17:44,280 --> 00:17:47,100
and our support engineers end
up discussing with customers.

462
00:17:47,100 --> 00:17:49,260
So I wanted to just give you
maybe a bit of an insight

463
00:17:49,260 --> 00:17:51,633
into two things that
we hear very regularly.

464
00:17:52,650 --> 00:17:54,960
And that other phrase
is, "Roll the fiber,"

465
00:17:54,960 --> 00:17:57,087
or "I'm gonna put a loop on that."

466
00:17:58,440 --> 00:17:59,640
I see a few people nodding here.

467
00:17:59,640 --> 00:18:01,680
Maybe you've heard that or experienced it.

468
00:18:01,680 --> 00:18:02,910
For those of you that have not worked

469
00:18:02,910 --> 00:18:04,490
with physical fiber equipment,

470
00:18:04,490 --> 00:18:06,720
at the bottom there we've
got what's called an SFP,

471
00:18:06,720 --> 00:18:08,880
a small form factor pluggable module.

472
00:18:08,880 --> 00:18:12,420
And on the right-hand side
we have some duplex fiber

473
00:18:12,420 --> 00:18:14,550
with LC connectors on the end of it.

474
00:18:14,550 --> 00:18:17,400
And the module at the
bottom is what is sitting

475
00:18:17,400 --> 00:18:19,320
in those various pieces
of network equipment

476
00:18:19,320 --> 00:18:21,090
on each end of this connection.

477
00:18:21,090 --> 00:18:21,930
And you might be able to see

478
00:18:21,930 --> 00:18:23,160
in very small writing on there,

479
00:18:23,160 --> 00:18:25,140
it's marked TX and RX.

480
00:18:25,140 --> 00:18:27,510
So that's transmit and receive.

481
00:18:27,510 --> 00:18:29,640
So what happens there on the transmit side

482
00:18:29,640 --> 00:18:31,400
is there is a laser inside that module

483
00:18:31,400 --> 00:18:34,040
that is firing the light out of it.

484
00:18:34,040 --> 00:18:35,160
And when it gets to the other end,

485
00:18:35,160 --> 00:18:36,630
it needs to go into the receive side

486
00:18:36,630 --> 00:18:38,460
of the other connection.

487
00:18:38,460 --> 00:18:41,190
So just to illustrate
that point a little bit,

488
00:18:41,190 --> 00:18:43,470
this would be just two
devices next to each other

489
00:18:43,470 --> 00:18:45,510
with a single duplex fiber cable

490
00:18:45,510 --> 00:18:47,040
that you would just plug in.

491
00:18:47,040 --> 00:18:47,940
This is what would happen.

492
00:18:47,940 --> 00:18:51,390
Transmit would be connected
to receive and vice versa.

493
00:18:51,390 --> 00:18:52,290
We'd all be having a good day.

494
00:18:52,290 --> 00:18:54,540
Packets would be flowing, no problem.

495
00:18:54,540 --> 00:18:56,030
But when you put this
in the context of a code

496
00:18:56,030 --> 00:18:59,610
or location facility, we've
now introduced a meet-me room.

497
00:18:59,610 --> 00:19:01,860
Now, there are no actual standards

498
00:19:01,860 --> 00:19:04,200
for how to do this kind of cabling.

499
00:19:04,200 --> 00:19:06,360
There's some, I guess, best practices

500
00:19:06,360 --> 00:19:07,650
that have been adopted in terms

501
00:19:07,650 --> 00:19:09,870
of where you cross over those pairs.

502
00:19:09,870 --> 00:19:12,960
So typically between your
rack and the meet-me room,

503
00:19:12,960 --> 00:19:14,910
the fiber will have been crossed over.

504
00:19:14,910 --> 00:19:17,730
And if we take that simple
example on the screen there,

505
00:19:17,730 --> 00:19:19,410
you've got two sides of a connection here,

506
00:19:19,410 --> 00:19:20,580
a single meet-me room.

507
00:19:20,580 --> 00:19:22,350
The fibers have been crossed on one side,

508
00:19:22,350 --> 00:19:23,640
crossed on the other.

509
00:19:23,640 --> 00:19:25,890
The patch in the middle
is just a simple fiber

510
00:19:25,890 --> 00:19:27,660
between those ports.

511
00:19:27,660 --> 00:19:29,010
That unravels quite nicely,

512
00:19:29,010 --> 00:19:30,660
and you end up with transmit to receive

513
00:19:30,660 --> 00:19:31,680
and vice versa again.

514
00:19:31,680 --> 00:19:32,513
All good.

515
00:19:33,600 --> 00:19:34,560
The other variation, though,

516
00:19:34,560 --> 00:19:37,110
is when you start adding
in multiple meet-me rooms,

517
00:19:37,110 --> 00:19:40,020
other providers, other
pieces of equipment,

518
00:19:40,020 --> 00:19:41,940
and before you know it,
you've got a situation

519
00:19:41,940 --> 00:19:44,670
where these fibers have
been crossed multiple times.

520
00:19:44,670 --> 00:19:47,700
So when you hear the
phrase roll the fiber,

521
00:19:47,700 --> 00:19:49,350
what they literally mean is swap,

522
00:19:49,350 --> 00:19:50,823
transmit, and receive around.

523
00:19:51,660 --> 00:19:54,240
I've lost track of the number
of times I've visited racks

524
00:19:54,240 --> 00:19:55,380
where I've seen the little clips

525
00:19:55,380 --> 00:19:57,390
on an LC fiber connector broken off

526
00:19:57,390 --> 00:19:59,370
so that the fibers can be swapped around.

527
00:19:59,370 --> 00:20:01,440
It's a very, very common thing.

528
00:20:01,440 --> 00:20:03,390
I wish it was totally
standardized everywhere,

529
00:20:03,390 --> 00:20:04,500
but unfortunately it's not.

530
00:20:04,500 --> 00:20:06,570
So that's what that means if you hear that

531
00:20:06,570 --> 00:20:09,020
when you're debugging a connection.

532
00:20:09,020 --> 00:20:12,000
The other phrase is putting a loop on it.

533
00:20:12,000 --> 00:20:13,890
So what I'm showing you here, very simply,

534
00:20:13,890 --> 00:20:15,540
again, these are just two SFPs,

535
00:20:15,540 --> 00:20:18,540
two devices that are
connected via a meet-me room,

536
00:20:18,540 --> 00:20:20,610
and perhaps the connection
isn't coming up.

537
00:20:20,610 --> 00:20:22,050
And what we wanna do here is identify

538
00:20:22,050 --> 00:20:23,280
where's the potential problem.

539
00:20:23,280 --> 00:20:24,690
Do we have some broken fiber?

540
00:20:24,690 --> 00:20:26,160
What's the issue?

541
00:20:26,160 --> 00:20:28,320
So what will happen here
is you'll hear someone say,

542
00:20:28,320 --> 00:20:29,820
I'm gonna put a loop on that connection

543
00:20:29,820 --> 00:20:33,663
facing towards AWS or
facing towards this carrier.

544
00:20:34,620 --> 00:20:36,210
What that means is in that meet-me room,

545
00:20:36,210 --> 00:20:37,860
they might unplug that fiber,

546
00:20:37,860 --> 00:20:39,600
that cross-connect that we had,

547
00:20:39,600 --> 00:20:42,000
and quite simply, they will
just loop the two together

548
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:43,620
on one side.

549
00:20:43,620 --> 00:20:47,040
So on the AWS side, our
laser is firing light out.

550
00:20:47,040 --> 00:20:48,720
It gets to that port in the meet-me room.

551
00:20:48,720 --> 00:20:51,810
It gets turned right back
around, sent back to AWS.

552
00:20:51,810 --> 00:20:53,520
And now, in those CloudWatch metrics,

553
00:20:53,520 --> 00:20:56,430
you would see light level being received.

554
00:20:56,430 --> 00:20:57,720
It's not always true that the connection

555
00:20:57,720 --> 00:20:58,560
would come up as such,

556
00:20:58,560 --> 00:21:00,990
but you can see that
that loop has been made.

557
00:21:00,990 --> 00:21:02,730
And even better, you
could see the transition

558
00:21:02,730 --> 00:21:05,760
where there was no loop
at all, no light flowing.

559
00:21:05,760 --> 00:21:06,660
You loop it, it's good.

560
00:21:06,660 --> 00:21:09,300
So now you know the path from AWS

561
00:21:09,300 --> 00:21:11,220
to the meet-me room is good.

562
00:21:11,220 --> 00:21:13,200
The same could be done on the
other side with the carrier,

563
00:21:13,200 --> 00:21:14,640
and it could be done at various places

564
00:21:14,640 --> 00:21:16,260
all the way down the path

565
00:21:16,260 --> 00:21:19,050
to troubleshoot a problem like this.

566
00:21:19,050 --> 00:21:21,920
So they're the two phrases
you're likely to hear.

567
00:21:21,920 --> 00:21:23,220
I thought I would share it with you,

568
00:21:23,220 --> 00:21:25,230
because as I say, our support organization

569
00:21:25,230 --> 00:21:27,840
work with customers
regularly on these things.

570
00:21:27,840 --> 00:21:29,790
And quite often, we find customers

571
00:21:29,790 --> 00:21:33,270
don't necessarily understand
these concepts, which I get.

572
00:21:33,270 --> 00:21:35,463
So hopefully, this clarifies that process.

573
00:21:37,290 --> 00:21:38,550
The last thing I wanted to talk about

574
00:21:38,550 --> 00:21:41,250
in terms of physical
connectivity is MACSEC.

575
00:21:41,250 --> 00:21:44,010
So MACSEC is enabled at the port level,

576
00:21:44,010 --> 00:21:45,150
as I mentioned earlier.

577
00:21:45,150 --> 00:21:46,320
When you request your port,

578
00:21:46,320 --> 00:21:47,520
you check that box at the bottom,

579
00:21:47,520 --> 00:21:50,940
and if it's available for that
bandwidth at that location,

580
00:21:50,940 --> 00:21:53,370
it's now available for you to consume.

581
00:21:53,370 --> 00:21:57,600
MACSEC encrypts the traffic
between two Layer 2 devices.

582
00:21:57,600 --> 00:21:59,370
So if you've got a piece of equipment

583
00:21:59,370 --> 00:22:00,750
in that co-location facility,

584
00:22:00,750 --> 00:22:03,240
and you connect them together
via the cross-connects,

585
00:22:03,240 --> 00:22:04,350
no problem.

586
00:22:04,350 --> 00:22:06,300
If you're connecting outside that facility

587
00:22:06,300 --> 00:22:07,890
to perhaps your data center,

588
00:22:07,890 --> 00:22:09,300
as long as your carrier is passing

589
00:22:09,300 --> 00:22:11,130
through all the Layer 2 traffic,

590
00:22:11,130 --> 00:22:12,900
then you can establish a MACSEC connection

591
00:22:12,900 --> 00:22:15,200
between those two devices.

592
00:22:15,200 --> 00:22:17,700
Once that traffic gets into AWS,

593
00:22:17,700 --> 00:22:19,110
we encrypt all of the traffic

594
00:22:19,110 --> 00:22:21,330
between AWS-secured facilities.

595
00:22:21,330 --> 00:22:23,460
So that MACSEC session
is between your device

596
00:22:23,460 --> 00:22:26,013
and the Direct Connect
device in that location.

597
00:22:27,140 --> 00:22:31,110
The keys for this session
are generated by you.

598
00:22:31,110 --> 00:22:34,860
They're stored inside KMS,
sorry, in Secrets Manager,

599
00:22:34,860 --> 00:22:38,700
and you can then rotate these
if you need to over time.

600
00:22:38,700 --> 00:22:40,920
You have a choice when you
configure MACSEC as well

601
00:22:40,920 --> 00:22:43,200
in terms of what you want
to do with the encryption.

602
00:22:43,200 --> 00:22:44,850
So you can choose no encryption,

603
00:22:44,850 --> 00:22:46,530
maybe that's your starting point.

604
00:22:46,530 --> 00:22:47,730
If this was part of a plan

605
00:22:47,730 --> 00:22:49,650
that you were gonna
enable MACSEC later on,

606
00:22:49,650 --> 00:22:52,020
you'd set it to no encrypt.

607
00:22:52,020 --> 00:22:53,820
There's also then should encrypt,

608
00:22:53,820 --> 00:22:56,370
where the two devices
will try and establish

609
00:22:56,370 --> 00:22:57,780
an encrypted connection between them,

610
00:22:57,780 --> 00:23:00,240
your device to ours, but if it fails,

611
00:23:00,240 --> 00:23:01,920
the connection will still come up.

612
00:23:01,920 --> 00:23:03,690
So that's quite a common stage to go to

613
00:23:03,690 --> 00:23:06,000
as you're rolling out MACSEC connectivity.

614
00:23:06,000 --> 00:23:08,100
You enable it, you set
it to should connect.

615
00:23:08,100 --> 00:23:09,780
That now effectively lets you test it

616
00:23:09,780 --> 00:23:10,640
because if you get it right,

617
00:23:10,640 --> 00:23:13,260
the connection will come up
and you'll see it encrypted.

618
00:23:13,260 --> 00:23:16,140
If it doesn't work, you haven't
interrupted the connection.

619
00:23:16,140 --> 00:23:17,910
And then the final one is must encrypt,

620
00:23:17,910 --> 00:23:19,500
which is exactly what it sounds like.

621
00:23:19,500 --> 00:23:21,360
If we can't establish the encryption

622
00:23:21,360 --> 00:23:22,280
between the two devices

623
00:23:22,280 --> 00:23:23,880
the connection will stay down

624
00:23:23,880 --> 00:23:26,880
and all your virtual interfaces
will be down as well.

625
00:23:26,880 --> 00:23:28,440
So talking of virtual interfaces,

626
00:23:28,440 --> 00:23:31,193
I'm gonna hand over to Josh
to talk about those with you.

627
00:23:32,280 --> 00:23:33,713
- All right, thank you, Steve.

628
00:23:34,950 --> 00:23:38,610
Yeah, so just taking a look at
the virtual interfaces here,

629
00:23:38,610 --> 00:23:40,710
just really quick, just to level set,

630
00:23:40,710 --> 00:23:43,560
Steve kind of alluded to
it, but virtual interface,

631
00:23:43,560 --> 00:23:46,260
that's the VLAN and the BGP, right?

632
00:23:46,260 --> 00:23:49,920
I know you kind of like talk
down about BGP, but I like it.

633
00:23:49,920 --> 00:23:52,530
So we have three main types

634
00:23:52,530 --> 00:23:54,150
and I'm gonna go into
some details on them.

635
00:23:54,150 --> 00:23:55,830
So don't panic.

636
00:23:55,830 --> 00:23:57,660
Public, private and transit.

637
00:23:57,660 --> 00:24:02,220
So public is for connecting
to public AWS endpoints,

638
00:24:02,220 --> 00:24:03,810
S3, that sort of thing.

639
00:24:03,810 --> 00:24:06,030
Private for getting to VPCs.

640
00:24:06,030 --> 00:24:08,160
Transit for getting to transit
gateways and cloud ones

641
00:24:08,160 --> 00:24:09,760
and then to VPCs.

642
00:24:09,760 --> 00:24:11,760
And then we also have the concept

643
00:24:11,760 --> 00:24:13,980
of a hosted virtual interface,

644
00:24:13,980 --> 00:24:16,560
not to be confused with
the hosted connection.

645
00:24:16,560 --> 00:24:19,920
This is a virtual interface owned

646
00:24:19,920 --> 00:24:22,500
by another account's connection.

647
00:24:22,500 --> 00:24:25,290
They configure all the
BGP and all of that stuff

648
00:24:25,290 --> 00:24:28,380
and then you attach it
to your VPC, essentially.

649
00:24:28,380 --> 00:24:30,270
So sometimes that's like
an infrastructure account

650
00:24:30,270 --> 00:24:31,103
or something like that.

651
00:24:31,103 --> 00:24:33,180
(inhales)

652
00:24:33,180 --> 00:24:36,220
So we'll start with
public virtual interfaces.

653
00:24:36,220 --> 00:24:38,820
I'm not gonna go into
super detail on these

654
00:24:38,820 --> 00:24:40,290
'cause I'm kind of hoping you know

655
00:24:40,290 --> 00:24:43,140
at least some level of
understanding about these,

656
00:24:43,140 --> 00:24:44,880
but public virtual interface,

657
00:24:44,880 --> 00:24:47,733
these are, as I said,
connects you to any region.

658
00:24:48,750 --> 00:24:51,780
These are, you use public IPs for peering.

659
00:24:51,780 --> 00:24:55,110
We have some ability to scope these down.

660
00:24:55,110 --> 00:24:57,520
I'll explain that a little later on.

661
00:24:57,520 --> 00:25:01,830
But essentially what it is is
your own personal connection

662
00:25:01,830 --> 00:25:03,130
to the public side of AWS.

663
00:25:06,570 --> 00:25:09,120
To talk about private virtual interfaces,

664
00:25:09,120 --> 00:25:11,640
we have to kind of go back in time first.

665
00:25:11,640 --> 00:25:14,160
We have to go before 2017,

666
00:25:14,160 --> 00:25:16,060
which feels like the way back machine.

667
00:25:17,250 --> 00:25:21,570
Back then, Direct Connect was
kind of a regional service.

668
00:25:21,570 --> 00:25:26,190
So what you had was your
Direct Connect was in a region

669
00:25:26,190 --> 00:25:27,660
and you could connect to your VPCs

670
00:25:27,660 --> 00:25:28,910
that were in that region.

671
00:25:29,790 --> 00:25:32,790
So in my example here, I have US East 1

672
00:25:32,790 --> 00:25:35,130
and I have my VPC in US East 1

673
00:25:35,130 --> 00:25:37,473
and my connection is in US East 1.

674
00:25:38,550 --> 00:25:40,620
I can still connect to multiple VPCs,

675
00:25:40,620 --> 00:25:43,800
but one VPC per virtual interface.

676
00:25:43,800 --> 00:25:45,840
And this is where that concept

677
00:25:45,840 --> 00:25:47,460
of an associated region comes in,

678
00:25:47,460 --> 00:25:48,480
which you may have seen if you've

679
00:25:48,480 --> 00:25:50,190
used Direct Connect at all

680
00:25:50,190 --> 00:25:52,990
because you can still
use this architecture.

681
00:25:52,990 --> 00:25:57,990
Then we kind of moved on a little bit

682
00:25:59,460 --> 00:26:03,800
to this architecture using
Direct Connect Gateway.

683
00:26:03,800 --> 00:26:06,660
So these are still private
virtual interfaces,

684
00:26:06,660 --> 00:26:10,110
but what these do, what
Direct Connect Gateway does

685
00:26:10,110 --> 00:26:12,600
is allows you to bring all
your private virtual interfaces

686
00:26:12,600 --> 00:26:15,630
into one Direct Connect Gateway.

687
00:26:15,630 --> 00:26:17,140
Those can be global from anywhere

688
00:26:17,140 --> 00:26:20,940
and you can then attach
your VPCs anywhere as well.

689
00:26:20,940 --> 00:26:23,910
So you can go kind of
from anywhere to anywhere.

690
00:26:23,910 --> 00:26:27,693
I mean, from on-prem
to VPC, VPC to on-prem.

691
00:26:30,530 --> 00:26:32,430
Then we started to get into the sort of

692
00:26:32,430 --> 00:26:34,893
the transit gateway Cloud WAN world.

693
00:26:36,210 --> 00:26:38,760
You've probably come
across those services.

694
00:26:38,760 --> 00:26:40,740
So we introduced transit
virtual interfaces,

695
00:26:40,740 --> 00:26:44,070
those very similar, similar idea.

696
00:26:44,070 --> 00:26:45,780
You connect to regionally,

697
00:26:45,780 --> 00:26:47,910
you can connect to transit gateways,

698
00:26:47,910 --> 00:26:51,730
Cloud WANs in different
regions, add those on.

699
00:26:51,730 --> 00:26:53,340
One thing to note there,

700
00:26:53,340 --> 00:26:55,140
you cannot mix and match there.

701
00:26:55,140 --> 00:26:58,560
You can't add VGWs and TGWs

702
00:26:58,560 --> 00:27:00,390
and you can't add transit
VIFs and private VIFs

703
00:27:00,390 --> 00:27:02,010
to the same ones.

704
00:27:02,010 --> 00:27:03,860
Just something to keep in mind there.

705
00:27:05,910 --> 00:27:08,910
And then just one other thing
I wanted to point out here,

706
00:27:08,910 --> 00:27:12,453
not necessarily a VIF type,
but kind of a setting on a VIF,

707
00:27:13,560 --> 00:27:15,300
private or transit VIF at least,

708
00:27:15,300 --> 00:27:16,980
is something called site link.

709
00:27:16,980 --> 00:27:21,360
This allows you to take your
traffic from one DX location

710
00:27:21,360 --> 00:27:25,230
to another DX location,
ride the AWS backbone.

711
00:27:25,230 --> 00:27:27,600
The nice thing is, and
you can see I created

712
00:27:27,600 --> 00:27:29,190
a lovely little GIF.

713
00:27:29,190 --> 00:27:30,930
You can just click the button

714
00:27:30,930 --> 00:27:32,250
and you'll start seeing the route show

715
00:27:32,250 --> 00:27:33,083
up on the other side.

716
00:27:33,083 --> 00:27:35,790
So you can kind of use
it as needed, right?

717
00:27:35,790 --> 00:27:37,883
You don't even have to
keep it on all the time.

718
00:27:42,120 --> 00:27:44,310
So taking a quick look at monitoring,

719
00:27:44,310 --> 00:27:45,570
these are sort of building on the things

720
00:27:45,570 --> 00:27:46,800
that Steve talked about before,

721
00:27:46,800 --> 00:27:50,190
but for virtual interfaces,

722
00:27:50,190 --> 00:27:53,570
we also have the bits per
second, ingress, egress,

723
00:27:53,570 --> 00:27:55,950
and packets per second,
so just give you the idea

724
00:27:55,950 --> 00:27:58,830
of what traffic is going
over those connections.

725
00:27:58,830 --> 00:28:00,810
And then we also have an
offering under CloudWatch

726
00:28:00,810 --> 00:28:03,810
called CloudWatch Network
Synthetic Monitor.

727
00:28:03,810 --> 00:28:05,490
That's actually sending real traffic.

728
00:28:05,490 --> 00:28:09,570
So you configure an
endpoint in your subnets

729
00:28:09,570 --> 00:28:12,720
and you configure, you
give us an endpoint on-prem

730
00:28:12,720 --> 00:28:15,693
and we send ICMP or TCP
traffic, you choose,

731
00:28:16,560 --> 00:28:19,140
and we return roundtrip time and

732
00:28:19,140 --> 00:28:20,640
packet loss metrics to you.

733
00:28:20,640 --> 00:28:23,160
There's also a network
health indicator metric

734
00:28:23,160 --> 00:28:24,300
that comes back.

735
00:28:24,300 --> 00:28:25,230
What that is,

736
00:28:25,230 --> 00:28:27,390
it's us looking at all
of our internal metrics

737
00:28:27,390 --> 00:28:29,940
for everything from the subnet all the way

738
00:28:29,940 --> 00:28:32,700
to the direct connect endpoint
that you're connected to,

739
00:28:32,700 --> 00:28:34,320
just to give you kind of a quick look

740
00:28:34,320 --> 00:28:36,840
if you're having a network issue to say,

741
00:28:36,840 --> 00:28:38,850
oh, that's definitely an AWS problem,

742
00:28:38,850 --> 00:28:40,320
I can go yell at them,

743
00:28:40,320 --> 00:28:42,873
or I need to go investigate my network.

744
00:28:46,320 --> 00:28:48,750
And so to troubleshooting
virtual interfaces,

745
00:28:48,750 --> 00:28:53,750
so again, layer one, you should be fine

746
00:28:54,750 --> 00:28:57,690
'cause you've been through
Steve's presentation,

747
00:28:57,690 --> 00:28:59,730
but again, that's kind of the first thing.

748
00:28:59,730 --> 00:29:00,870
If your layer one's not up,

749
00:29:00,870 --> 00:29:02,870
you're not gonna get any further, right?

750
00:29:03,990 --> 00:29:06,510
The next thing to check if
your VIF's not coming up

751
00:29:06,510 --> 00:29:09,780
is layer two, so making
sure your VLAN tags

752
00:29:09,780 --> 00:29:11,550
match on both sides.

753
00:29:11,550 --> 00:29:13,680
The other thing we see pretty commonly,

754
00:29:13,680 --> 00:29:16,610
especially when you start adding
in partners and providers,

755
00:29:16,610 --> 00:29:20,010
they love to use these
encapsulation technologies.

756
00:29:20,010 --> 00:29:22,470
Again, totally fine, no problem,

757
00:29:22,470 --> 00:29:25,560
but we need to make sure
once they are facing,

758
00:29:25,560 --> 00:29:27,750
like the port facing AWS,
those are stripped off

759
00:29:27,750 --> 00:29:30,200
and it's just the VLAN of
your virtual interface.

760
00:29:32,070 --> 00:29:35,250
Then once you get up another layer,

761
00:29:35,250 --> 00:29:39,090
you're into sort of BGP layer
three sort of issues, right?

762
00:29:39,090 --> 00:29:44,090
So you can kind of see it
goes two different ways.

763
00:29:44,910 --> 00:29:48,480
If you're seeing in your BGP logs,

764
00:29:48,480 --> 00:29:52,020
stuff getting stuck in
idle, connect active,

765
00:29:52,020 --> 00:29:54,900
it's probably a network
connectivity problem.

766
00:29:54,900 --> 00:29:56,370
If you're getting over that,

767
00:29:56,370 --> 00:29:58,713
you're getting into
open sent, open confirm,

768
00:29:59,550 --> 00:30:01,893
it's a BGP parameter
problem more than likely.

769
00:30:06,090 --> 00:30:09,840
Okay, so I wanna talk a
little bit about routing

770
00:30:09,840 --> 00:30:12,963
